</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Accurate interpretation of posttherapeutic images obtained in radiation oncology patients requires familiarity with modern radiation therapy techniques and their expected effects on normal tissues. Three-dimensional conformal external-beam radiation therapy techniques (eg, intensity-modulated radiation therapy, stereotactic body radiation therapy), although they are designed to reduce the amount of normal tissue exposed to high-dose radiation, inevitably increase the amount of normal tissue that is exposed to low-dose radiation, with the potential for resultant changes that may evolve over time. Currently available internal radiation therapy techniques (eg, arterial radioembolization for hepatic malignancies, brachytherapy for prostate cancer and gynecologic cancers) also carry risks of possible injury to adjacent nontargeted tissues. The sensitivity of tissues to radiation exposure varies according to the tissue type but is generally proportional to the rate of cellular division, with rapidly regenerating tissues such as intestinal mucosa being the most radiosensitive. The characteristic response to radiation-induced injury likewise varies according to tissue type, with atrophy predominating in epithelial tissue whereas fibrosis predominates in stromal tissue. Moreover, changes in irradiated tissues evolve over time: In the liver, decreased attenuation at computed tomography and increased signal intensity at T2-weighted magnetic resonance imaging reflect hyperemia and edema in the early posttherapeutic period; later, veno-occlusive changes alter the hepatic enhancement pattern; and finally, fibrosis develops in some patients. In the small bowel, wall thickening and mucosal hyperenhancement predominate initially, whereas luminal narrowing is the most prominent feature of chronic enteropathy. Correlation of posttherapeutic images with images used for treatment planning may be helpful when interpreting complex cases.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2013</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.332125119">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.332125119">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig01.jpeg" height="1084" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig01" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Plot shows that the degree of cellular radiosensitivity is directly proportional to the rate of cellular regeneration (from rapid to absent) and inversely proportional to the degree of cellular differentiation (from undifferentiated to fully differentiated). It may be helpful to recall these relationships when considering the timing, severity, and persistence of radiation-related changes seen at imaging, although not all of the tissues listed are visible radiologically.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig01">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig02.jpeg" height="867" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig02" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Schematic of two-dimensional radiation therapy for prostate cancer shows four external beams (shaded color bars) directed at right angles toward an axial body section. Before computed tomography (CT) was available for clinical use, radiation treatment planning was based on radiographs obtained in orthogonal planes with osseous landmarks. The bladder <i>(B)</i> and rectum <i>(R)</i>, because of their positions immediately anterior and posterior to the prostate <i>(P)</i>, received relatively high doses, as did the femoral heads with their radiosensitive marrow directly in the path of the beams.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig02">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig03.jpeg" height="875" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig03" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Axial CT image with color overlays shows the plan for 3D conformal external-beam radiation therapy in a patient with prostate cancer. With CT used to localize the target volume and plot the radiation dose contours, the beams need not be orthogonal. In this example, six beams are deployed with the use of oblique angulation and collimation to exclude the rectum from the highest dose contours (central pink contour lines).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig03">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig04.jpeg" height="983" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig04" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Axial CT image with color overlays shows the plan for IMRT in a patient with prostate cancer. Each of the green-shaded grids outside the body shows a variable radiation dose distribution across a two-dimensional representation of the target volume. The intersection of the precisely modeled beams creates a complex 3D shape that closely approximates the contours of the tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig04">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig05.jpeg" height="1146" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig05" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Axial CT image with color overlays shows the plan for SBRT with 12 beams (paired green lines enclose each numbered beam) for treatment of a central hepatic mass. The closely spaced pink, orange, and yellow rings near the target zone, which are analogous to altitude markings on a topographic map, show a steep gradient from high to low doses. Most of the liver and other abdominal structures lying within the individual beams will receive only low-dose radiation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig05">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig06.jpeg" height="1001" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig06" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Schematic shows transperineally implanted brachytherapy seeds (red dots) irradiating a tumor within the prostate <i>(P)</i>. The key adjacent structures, the bladder <i>(B)</i> and rectum <i>(R)</i>, are largely spared because of short-range penetration by the low-energy rays; however, weak penetration also limits the effect of therapy on microscopic infiltrative disease that extends beyond the prostate capsule.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig06">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig07.jpeg" height="922" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Schematic shows radioembolization of a liver tumor <i>(T)</i> with <sup>90</sup>Y-labeled microspheres (red dots) delivered by means of selective distal hepatic artery catheterization. A more proximal hepatic artery catheter position would be used for radioembolization of a larger hepatic volume, such as an entire segment or lobe.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig08a.jpeg" height="1124" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig08a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig08b.jpeg" height="859" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig08b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig09a.jpeg" height="1111" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig09a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig09b.jpeg" height="1178" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig09b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig09c.jpeg" height="1154" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig09c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig10a.jpeg" height="896" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig10b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1278" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig10c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1017" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig11a.jpeg" height="1037" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig11b.jpeg" height="1010" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig11c.jpeg" height="1006" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig11d.jpeg" height="918" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig11e.jpeg" height="919" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11e</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig11e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig12.jpeg" height="1034" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Impaired hepatocyte function in a 70-year-old man who received a dose of 60 Gy (20 fractions) to the liver for unresectable hepatocellular carcinoma. Axial T1-weighted fat-saturated hepatobiliary phase MR image obtained 20 minutes after a gadoxetic acid (ie, Gd-EOB-DTPA) injection shows a sharply marginated zone of diminished enhancement (arrowheads) in the irradiated region of the liver, a finding that represents impaired hepatocyte function. Normal biliary excretion from the right hepatic lobe is seen in the central bile ducts (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig13a.jpeg" height="1256" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig13b.jpeg" height="1256" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig14a.jpeg" height="1166" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div clas