ownloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig14e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig14f.jpeg" height="1109" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14f</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig14f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig15a.jpeg" height="1125" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig15b.jpeg" height="1173" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig15c.jpeg" height="1108" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig16a.jpeg" height="986" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig16b.jpeg" height="1010" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig17.jpeg" height="1052" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Pancreatic atrophy in a 50-year-old man who underwent radiation therapy with a dose of 55.8 Gy to the surgical bed after a left adrenalectomy for locally recurrent adrenocortical carcinoma. Axial CT image obtained 8 years after the completion of radiation therapy shows wisps of soft tissue representing markedly atrophic parenchyma in the expected region of the pancreatic body and tail (arrow). A metastasis is seen in the right adrenal gland (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig18a.jpeg" height="1124" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig18b.jpeg" height="1128" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig19a.jpeg" height="1024" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig19b.jpeg" height="960" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig20.jpeg" height="1057" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span> Chronic radiation-induced enteropathy in a 63-year-old woman with severe episodic vomiting and diarrhea and intermittent partial obstructions of the small bowel 2 years after receiving a dose of 50.4 Gy to the pelvis for adjuvant treatment of endometrial cancer. The patient previously had undergone a hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows angulation and tethering of small bowel loops (white arrow), findings suggestive of adhesions. Circumferential wall thickening and fold thickening with luminal narrowing (black arrow) are seen centrally. Such changes can occur in patients who undergo surgery alone for treatment of endometrial cancer, but they are more frequent after additional radiation therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig21.jpeg" height="1112" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Rectovesical fistula in a 56-year-old man who underwent neoadjuvant external-beam radiation therapy (estimated dose, 50 Gy) for locally invasive rectal carcinoma. Excretory phase CT urogram shows a large channel (arrows) communicating between the bladder and rectum. A rectovesical fistula resulting from moderate-dose radiation therapy is relatively rare and may be difficult to differentiate from a rectovesical fistula occurring as a complication of surgery or malignant progression.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig22.jpeg" height="857" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span> Renal changes after therapeutic irradiation in a 35-year-old woman who received a dose of 45 Gy in 25 fractions to the left chest wall and paraspinal region for Ewing sarcoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 2 years after treatment demonstrates cortical thinning and diminished enhancement in the medial aspect of the left kidney (arrow). Recurrent tumor is seen along the anterior chest wall (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig23.jpeg" height="1280" width="981" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span> Renal changes after therapeutic irradiation in a 44-year-old woman who received a dose of 45 Gy in 20 fractions to the left retroperitoneum for a high-grade fibrosarcoma, and, 5 years later, a dose of 54 Gy for recurrent tumor in the left chest wall. Sagittal reformatted CT image shows marked atrophy of both the upper and lower left renal poles (black arrows) in comparison with the spared interpolar region (arrowhead). The recurrent chest wall tumor (white arrow) also is seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig24.jpeg" height="997" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> Radiation-induced cystopathy in a 70-year-old man who underwent neoadjuvant external-beam radiation therapy (estimated dose, 50 Gy) for unresectable rectal carcinoma. Axial CT image obtained 2 months after treatment shows new circumferential bladder wall thickening (arrow) with mucosal hyperenhancement (arrowhead), classic CT findings of radiation-induced cystopathy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig25.jpeg" height="1010" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span> Cervical stenosis and uterine atrophy in a 37-year-old woman with pelvic pain after undergoing external-beam radiation therapy (estimated dose, 45–50 Gy) and tandem and ring brachytherapy for stage IIIB cervical carcinoma (dose, 30 Gy). Transvaginal US image obtained 4 months after the completion of therapy demonstrates a complex fluid collection within the dilated endometrial canal (arrows), a finding suggestive of hematometra due to cervical stenosis. Note the small size of the irradiated uterus (calipers, 4.6 × 2.5 cm). Cervical stenosis is rarely symptomatic.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig26a.jpeg" height="913" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig26a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig26b.jpeg" height="1159" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig26b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig27a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1118" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.332125119/asset/images/125119fig27b.jpeg" height="1126" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.332125119&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Mancuso M, Pasquali E, Giardullo P, et al. The radiation bystander effect and its potential implications for human health. <em>